liffe, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Smyth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ronan, Aidan, Brigid, Conor, Eoin, Malachy, Paddy.","English: variant of   Smith  . This form of the surname is particularly common Ireland."],"variants":[{"name":"Smith","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name denoting a worker in metal, especially iron, such as a blacksmith or farrier, from Middle English <i>smith</i> ‘smith’ (Old English <i>smith</i>, probably a derivative of <i>smītan</i> ‘to strike, hammer’). Early examples are also found in the Latin form   Faber  . Metal-working was one of the earliest occupations for which specialist skills were required, and its importance ensured that this term and its equivalents in other languages were the most widespread of all occupational surnames in Europe. Medieval smiths were important not only in making horseshoes, plowshares, and other domestic articles, but above all for their skill in forging swords, other weapons, and armor. This is also the most frequent of all surnames in the US. It is very common among African Americans and Native Americans (see also 5 below). This surname (in any of the two possible English senses; see also below) is also found in Haiti. See also   Smither  .","English: from Middle English <i>smithe</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old English <i>smiththe</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, occupational, for someone who worked in one, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Smitha in King's Nympton (Devon). Compare   Smithey  .","Irish and Scottish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Gobhann</b>, Irish <b>Mac Gabhann</b> ‘son of the smith’. See   McGowan  ."]}]},{"name":"Katherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of   Katherine  , also occasionally used in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":19,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Katherine Smyth was born in 1047, in Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England. She married Adam Le Savage. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1074, in her hometown, at the age of 27."},"et":{"1047–1074":"1047–1074","1049–1073":"1049–1073","1073–1098":"1073–1098","1049":"1049","1047":"1047","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","1074":"1074","1073":"1073","Stainesby, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"1047–1074":"1047–1074","1049–1073":"1049–1073","1073–1098":"1073–1098","1049":"1049","1047":"1047","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","1074":"1074","1073":"1073","Stainesby, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England"},"fr":{"1047–1074":"1047–1074","1049–1073":"1049–1073","1073–1098":"1073–1098","1049":"1049","1047":"1047","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","1074":"1074","1073":"1073","Stainesby, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Katherine Smyth est née en 1047, à Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, Angleterre. Elle a épousé Adam Le Savage. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Elle est dé